@article{Eyre-Walker2006a,
abstract = {The distribution of fitness effects of new mutations is a fundamental parameter in genetics. Here we present a new method by which the distribution can be estimated. The method is fairly robust to changes in population size and admixture, and it can be corrected for any residual effects if a model of the demography is available. We apply the method to extensively sampled single-nucleotide polymorphism data from humans and estimate the distribution of fitness effects for amino acid changing mutations. We show that a gamma distribution with a shape parameter of 0.23 provides a good fit to the data and we estimate that {\textgreater}50{\%} of mutations are likely to have mild effects, such that they reduce fitness by between one one-thousandth and one-tenth. We also infer that {\textless}15{\%} of new mutations are likely to have strongly deleterious effects. We estimate that on average a nonsynonymous mutation reduces fitness by a few percent and that the average strength of selection acting against a nonsynonymous polymorphism is approximately 9 x 10(-5). We argue that the relaxation of natural selection due to modern medicine and reduced variance in family size is not likely to lead to a rapid decline in genetic quality, but that it will be very difficult to locate most of the genes involved in complex genetic diseases.},
annote = {They propose a method to estimate the DFE from data of SNPs in humans (90 ind, 320 genes).
---------
BASIS:
They use the observed SFS to estimate the DFE
They get a DFE after fitting several parameters of the DFE model to the observed data, using a MCMC. 

This MCMC is made to get an estimate that fit the data by a random walk from a initial parameter value, each "step" is accepted of rejected based on the probability the new parameter value has. After millions of iterations, the parameters should be close to the real parameter value.

In their estimations, MCMC was run for a burn in of 1,000,000 steps before being sampled for a further 50,000,000 steps.
----------
THE METHOD:

The number of non-synonymous SNPs expected to found at a certain frequency depends on:
-the effective population size (Nes)
-mutation rate of that frequency category(ur)
-the [observed] number of non-synonymous mutations (Ln)
-time that a new deleterious mutation of strength spend between x and x+dx (H)
-probability of observing a mutation at a freq x in the population. (given the total number of alleles, is based on permutations)

The number of intron SNPs expected to found at a certain frequency depends on:
-the effective population size (Nes)
-mutation rate of that frequency category(ur)
-the [observed] number of intron mutations (Li)

Genes can have their own Ne and u, but they all share the same DFE.

----------
DEMOGRAPHY:

They run simulations to see how well this method behaves in different demographic scenarios. They try 3 different models:
-Population expansion
-Admixture (population divides in 2, evolve independently, then merge again)
-bottle neck
-----------
ACCOUNTING FOR DEMOGRAPHY

They realize that their estimated mean strength of selection might be overestimated by the demography, they try to correct it by:
1)Estimate the parameters of the DFE (gamma0 and lambda0) 
2)Estimate the demographic model using the neutral data.
